<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-30T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-30T21:00:00-05:00" n="152" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d152">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3776: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Nanking (<persName type="from">Peck</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-31T10:00:00+08:00">January 31, 1932—10
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 31—12:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>22. In execution of formulated plan the most important officers of the
                            Chinese Government have temporarily removed their offices from
                            Nanking.</p>
                        <p>Four Japanese destroyers have just arrived and anchored. I have
                            telephoned to the Japanese Consul in my capacity of Senior Consul and he
                            has again assured me that the Japanese vessels will not take the
                            initiative in fire action.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Legation.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>